snippet.textDisplay: Hey, in the future, brûlée your sugar before you put it on top of the crème. Once brûlée-d (or just caramelized), crush it up and then put the powder on top of the crème. Then use your torch to melt all the caramelized sugar back to one solid piece for you to break. This allows you to caramelize the sugar without burning it! I've done this before by putting sugar on a silicone baking mat and torching it. You can move swifter and should you burn some sugar, you can discard it!
snippet.textOriginal: Hey, in the future, brûlée your sugar before you put it on top of the crème. Once brûlée-d (or just caramelized), crush it up and then put the powder on top of the crème. Then use your torch to melt all the caramelized sugar back to one solid piece for you to break. This allows you to caramelize the sugar without burning it! snippet.textDisplay: in 2006, high school musical came out, which contained a line by zeke baylor about creme brulee: this creamy custard-like filling with a caramelized surface, which i've heard is really satisfying. and all 6 year old me wanted to do was try creme brulee. i looked up bakeries near me and my dad took me to two, neither of which had creme brulee. i then looked up recipes online and maybe it was the fact that i had a 3rd grade reading level but they all seemed way too advanced. I didn't get the chance to have creme brulee until 9 years later. needless to say, this title really came to punch me in the face. unsubscribed.

Important step when using canned coconut milk:

Put it in the fridge so the creamy fat separates on top. This will save you time (no reducing and less thickeners required) and makes it super creamy and thick.
